      interview: [
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is 'self' in Python?", a: "It represents the instance of the class. It allows us to access the attributes and methods of the specific object being called.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is inheritance?", a: "A mechanism where one class (child) copies all the properties and behaviors of another class (parent).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is a class?", a: "A blueprint for creating objects. It defines a set of attributes and methods that the objects will have.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is an object?", a: "An instance of a class that contains real values and data.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "Explain the difference between a class and an object.", a: "A class is the template (blueprint); an object is the actual building (instance).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is the constructor in Python?", a: "The __init__ method, which initializes an object's state when it is created.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What are instance variables?", a: "Variables that belong to a specific instance of a class, defined inside the __init__ method using self.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What are class variables?", a: "Variables shared across all instances of a class, defined directly within the class body.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "How do you call a parent class method?", a: "Using the super() function: super().method_name().", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is method overriding?", a: "Providing a specific implementation in a child class for a method that is already defined in its parent class.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is Encapsulation?", a: "Wrapping data and methods into a single unit (class) and restricting direct access to components.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "Explain Abstraction.", a: "Hiding the complex implementation details and showing only the necessary features of an object.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is Polymorphism?", a: "The ability of different objects to respond to the same method call in their unique ways.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "How do you define multiple inheritance?", a: "When a class inherits from more than one parent class.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is an inner class?", a: "A class defined inside another class.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is the purpose of the 'del' statement?", a: "To delete an object and free its memory (though garbage collection usually handles this).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is a namespace in Python OOP?", a: "A system that ensures unique names for objects in a program, like class namespaces and instance namespaces.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is the 'dir()' function used for?", a: "To list all the attributes and methods of an object.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is the difference between @staticmethod and @classmethod?", a: "@staticmethod does not take 'self' or 'cls'. @classmethod takes the class ('cls') as its first argument and can access class-level state.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Explain the concept of MRO.", a: "Method Resolution Order. It is the order in which Python searches for a method in a hierarchy of classes, specifically in multiple inheritance.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What are dunder (magic) methods?", a: "Methods with double underscores (e.g., __init__, __str__). They allow you to define standard behaviors like addition or printing for your classes.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "How do you implement data encapsulation?", a: "By using leading underscores (_ or __) to signal that variables are intended for internal use, and using properties to control access.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is the purpose of super()?", a: "It returns a proxy object that delegates method calls to a parent or sibling class of a type, common in single and multiple inheritance.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Explain '@property' vs getters/setters.", a: "@property allows you to define methods as attributes, providing a clean API while maintaining control over value setting/getting.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is an Abstract Base Class (ABC)?", a: "A class defined via the abc module that contains abstract methods which MUST be implemented by subclasses.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Explain 'Composition' over 'Inheritance'.", a: "Composition involves referencing instances of other classes as attributes instead of inheriting from them, leading to more flexible and less coupled designs.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "How do you implement a Mixin?", a: "By creating a small class with specific functionality and inheriting from it alongside other classes.", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is the difference between '__getattr__' and '__getattribute__'?", a: "__getattr__ is only called if the attribute isn't found. __getattribute__ is called for EVERY attribute access.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Explain 'Operator Overloading'.", a: "Defining the behavior of standard operators (like +, -, *) for user-defined classes by implementing dunder methods like __add__.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is the '__slots__' attribute?", a: "A list of strings used to restrict attribute creation to a fixed set, saving memory by not creating an instance __dict__.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "How does Python handle Multiple Inheritance collisions?", a: "Using the C3 Linearization algorithm to determine a consistent Method Resolution Order (MRO).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Explain 'Proxy' objects.", a: "Objects that wrap another object to control access, logging, or extra processing (often using __getattr__).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain the C3 Linearization algorithm.", a: "The algorithm Python uses to compute the Method Resolution Order (MRO) in complex inheritance structures.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "What are metaclasses?", a: "The 'classes of classes'. They define how a class behaves. By default, 'type' is the metaclass in Python.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Difference between __new__ and __init__?", a: "__new__ is for creating the instance (the actual constructor). __init__ is for initializing that instance (the initializer).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How would you implement a Singleton pattern in Python?", a: "Usually by overriding __new__ to return a cached instance, or using a decorator or a metaclass.", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain 'Duck Typing'.", a: "'If it walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, it's a duck.' Python cares about whether an object has specific methods, not its specific type.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "When would you use a Metaclass instead of a Decorator?", a: "When you need to modify the class structure itself during its creation, rather than just wrapping it after it's defined.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How does the 'super()' function work in multiple inheritance?", a: "It returns a proxy object that delegates calls to the NEXT class in the MRO, not necessarily the direct parent.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain the 'Data Descriptor' vs 'Non-Data Descriptor' protocol.", a: "Descriptors with __set__ are Data Descriptors and always override instance variables. Without __set__, they are Non-Data Descriptors.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How would you implement a 'Constant' attribute in a class?", a: "By using a property without a setter, or using a specialized Descriptor that raises an exception on __set__.", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain the security risks of '__dict__' access.", a: "It allows direct manipulation of object attributes, bypassing any logic in setters or encapsulation efforts.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "What is 'Interface Segregation' in the context of Python?", a: "Using small, focused Abstract Base Classes or Mixins to ensure classes only implement the behavior they actually need.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How does Python handle garbage collection for objects with '__del__' methods?", a: "It makes it more complex because __del__ can 'resurrect' the object, and circular references with __del__ used to be difficult to clean up before Python 3.4.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain 'Dynamic Dispatch' in Python.", a: "The process of selecting which implementation of a polymorphic method to call at runtime based on the object's type.", type: "Conceptual" }
      ]
